Title: Linking forum posts - analyze-4-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
I'm very confused about the use of light years as a unit in the equations. I've worked my way to the point where is understand that? \xA0r = (d x 206,265) / Angle but for the life of my I can't understand how you can throw in d = some value in light years and come of with a correct figure. Can anyone shed some light on how the units of Arc Seconds and Light Years are compatible?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
The number 206,265 actually has units attached to it!\xA0\xA0 It is the number of arc seconds in a radian.\xA0 So the arc-seconds 'cancel' on the right.\xA0 Thus, whatever units you use for 'r' (or 'd') will yield the other unknown in the same units.... This is the real advantage in using radians in the first place!

Input.threadtitle: Quick Energy Spectrum Plots on DS9 -- emission or absorption lines?
Input.posts:
When we're looking at the peaks and valleys produced in the quick energy spectrum that DS9 spits out from an x-ray source (for example, w49B) are we looking at an emission spectrum or a transmission spectrum?? That is, do the valleys fingerprint elements present (by virtue of the particular energies subtracted out of the blackbody spectrum) or do the peaks fingerprint elements elements present (by virtue of the the elements getting excited by x-ray radiation and then fluorescing at characteristic energies)? Does the answer depend on on which particular object we're examining? If so, what are the objects we'll be examining in this course that will contain emissions lines and what are the objects that will contain absorption lines? \xA0Are there any objects that show both in the same image?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
In terms of those in the second week lectures, you are looking at emission spectra, where the peak shows that a lot of photons of that particular energy were picked up by the detector. So, in this case the peaks are the fingerprint of the presence of a certain element. Of course that means in the absorption/transmission case, the opposite is true and the valleys become the fingerprint. It does indeed matter on the type of object you are looking at. A star for instance will emit radiation with a blackbody-like spectrum. The reason we see absorption lines in the solar spectrum is due to colder gas in the outer regions of the Sun which will absorb energy at the characteristic wavelengths for the element(s) it is composed of. When you have a lot of hot (ionized) gas, for instance in Cas A that was featured in the lecture, or a nebula with lots of star formation (being heated by very bright, very massive young stars), light is emitted only at the characteristic wavelengths for that element as the electrons recombine with the atoms and de-excite to a lower energy level.

Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Quick Energy Spectrum Plots on DS9 -- emission or absorption lines?
Input.posts:
When we're looking at the peaks and valleys produced in the quick energy spectrum that DS9 spits out from an x-ray source (for example, w49B) are we looking at an emission spectrum or a transmission spectrum?? That is, do the valleys fingerprint elements present (by virtue of the particular energies subtracted out of the blackbody spectrum) or do the peaks fingerprint elements elements present (by virtue of the the elements getting excited by x-ray radiation and then fluorescing at characteristic energies)? Does the answer depend on on which particular object we're examining? If so, what are the objects we'll be examining in this course that will contain emissions lines and what are the objects that will contain absorption lines? \xA0Are there any objects that show both in the same image?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
In terms of those in the second week lectures, you are looking at emission spectra, where the peak shows that a lot of photons of that particular energy were picked up by the detector. So, in this case the peaks are the fingerprint of the presence of a certain element. Of course that means in the absorption/transmission case, the opposite is true and the valleys become the fingerprint. It does indeed matter on the type of object you are looking at. A star for instance will emit radiation with a blackbody-like spectrum. The reason we see absorption lines in the solar spectrum is due to colder gas in the outer regions of the Sun which will absorb energy at the characteristic wavelengths for the element(s) it is composed of. When you have a lot of hot (ionized) gas, for instance in Cas A that was featured in the lecture, or a nebula with lots of star formation (being heated by very bright, very massive young stars), light is emitted only at the characteristic wavelengths for that element as the electrons recombine with the atoms and de-excite to a lower energy level.

Input.posts:
around 6:10 in video 3.1 professor Matilsky gives an example of knowing a star's spectral type and inferring its absolute magnitude from the HR diagram (such that knowing its apparent magnitude would tell its distance). But how would one know that the star is main sequence as opposed to a giant (which would be more luminous and more distant)? For B-V=+1.5, there seem to be a fair percentage of giants. (In the video the professor seems to indicate that we would know that its luminosity is 0.01 times the sun, but if we knew that independently we wouldn't need the HR diagram, I think.)
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Walter, mainn sequence stars are stars who are fusing hydrogen to make helium. On the HR diagram, all the main sequence starts lie on the same line starting from the youngest starts. Main sequence stars are bright and hot while red giants are dim and much cooler.
Instructor's post : Hi Walter, mainn sequence stars are stars who are fusing hydrogen to make helium. On the HR diagram, all the main sequence starts lie on the same line starting from the youngest starts. Main sequence stars are bright and hot while red giants are dim and much cooler.

Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
Hi guys, I'm just trying to see if I have understood the calculations regarding acceleration on the surface of K and White Dwarf stars. Firstly, Professor Matilsky looked at the acceleration at the surface of K star based on mass and radius to see if it could rotate with period 352 seconds. Secondly, he looked at the acceleration at the surface of the White Dwarf star using it's mass and radius to see if it could rotate with the same period while remaining gravitationally intact. So in summary it was a comparison between the 2 stars dimensions to see which could rotate with that period. Does that sound right?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Shane, sounds like you've got it. From the period and size of the object, you can get the speed and, since it is rotating in a circular path, the (centripetal) acceleration due to this rotation. As the acceleration due to gravity must be stronger than this to hold the object together, we find that the object rotates too fast for it to possibly be a K star, but that a white dwarf is small enough to be able to maintain such a fast rotation.
